Data is a data item composed of data examples and it may be of a various level of granularity and complexity. 
With regard to granularity, it can be a whole dataset (for instance, one main table and possibly other tables), or only a single table, or only a feature (e.g., a column of a table), or only an instance (e.g., row of a table), or a single feature-value pair. 
With regard to complexity, data examples are characterized by their datatype, which may be arbitrarily complex (e.g., instead of a table it can be an arbitrary graph).

DataCharacteristic is a distinguishing quality or property that distinguish one data from another.
Such characteristics are often statistical ones (e.g., the number of instances
or the number of features of a data set). They may be also informationtheoretic measures (e.g., class entropy of a categorical data set) or geometric measures of data complexity (e.g., the highest discriminatory power of any single feature in the data set).
Information about an algorithm, typically pseudocode or/and circuit, that describes a solution for the problem.
Provides name of the publication author.

The 'based on' property relates an Algorithm to some other 
Algorithm that provides a basic technique  for the first Algorithm.
This relation can help to derive the relevant pubications/ blog posts to the other algorithms that needed to understand this algorithm.

The 'belongs to' property relates an 'Problem' to a 'Complexity Class'. 
This relation can be helpful for researchers to explore the possibilities of quantum computing.
The 'over' property depicts over which 'Classical Algorithm' a 'Quantum Algorithm' or 'Hybrid Quantum-Classical Algorithm' achieves indicated expected speedup.
Answers the question:What is the implementation of this algorithm?
A relation between an machine learning algogorithm and description of its hyperparameter in a textual form.
Ansers the following question: Which algorithm is implemented by the particular implementation?
This property depicts over which 'Classical Algorithm' a 'Quantum Algorithm' or a 'Hybrid Quantum-Classical Algorithm' achieves indicated expected speedup.
This property relates two algorithms that solve the same problem, but the domain algorithm solves the problem more effitiently than the range algorithm.
This relation between two algorithms exist when an algorithm add improvements to another existing algorithm.
The 'realizes' property relates an 'Computational Resource' to a 'Computational Model'. This relation can be used in the future to derive devices, on which an Implementation is executable.
The 'realized in' property relates an 'Computational Model' to a 'Computational Resource'. This relation can be used in the future to derive devices, on which an Implementation is executable.

The 'depends on' property relates an 'Implementation' to a 'Software Tool'. 
This relation can be used to derive implementations that uses an specific framework, i. e. qiskit, TensorflowQuantum etc.
